Box Plots and Scatterplots In-Depth

Parts of a Boxplot

See boardwork.

Example: iris Sepal.Length

iris %>% head
# make boxplot of sepal length

#qplot note:  you need both x and y here

#  x = facet category
#  y = the actual data you're interested in (sepal length)


qplot(x=Species,
      y=Sepal.Length,
      data=iris,
      geom="boxplot",
      fill=Species)

Weird-looking boxplot examples!

The cirp data has some weird ones!

# let's boxplot YRSTUDY1

cirpData <- read_csv("CIRP_DATA_2014_CLEAN.csv")


cirpData %>% head
qplot(x=SEX,
      y=YRSTUDY1,
      data=cirpData,
      geom="boxplot")

Woah! What happened? Almost everyon chose 6, i.e., 4 years of english.

Think: 6, 6, 6, 6, 6, 6, 6, 6, 6, 6,6 ,6, 6, 6, 6,6, 4, 5, 7

When scatterplots make sense (and when they dont)

First, a good example: mpg dataset

mpg %>% head
#idea:  compare city and hwy fuel efficiency!

qplot(cty, 
      hwy, 
      data=mpg, 
      geom="point")

This is a clear positive relationship. That makes perfect sense: if a car is efficient in the city, of course its efficient on the hwy.

# try disp and hwy


qplot(displ,
      hwy,
      data=mpg)

This is a negative relationship. Makes sense! Bigger engines are less efficient.

Good Bad Example

# scatterplot of RATE01 and RATE03 (academic ability and compet)

qplot(x=RATE01,
      y=RATE03,
      data = cirpData,
      geom="point")

Woah! What happened? Scatterplots dont make sense for categorical data!! Cant tell how many points!

A possible fix: jitter.

qplot(x=RATE01,
      y=RATE03,
      data = cirpData,
      geom="point")+geom_jitter(width=1/20, alpha = 1/2)

Sampling

Population

The population is everyone (or everythign) were interested in.

Ex: All Americans Ex: All University studetns

Whoever you care about as an investigator.

Sample

Problem: populations are too darned big! We cant study everyone, since we have limited money and life spans!

Solution: Lets pick a subset of the population, and study that subset.

Another problem: is our sample representative?
